@conference{Lee20251031,
 abbrev_source_title = {Proc Asia South Pac Des Autom Conf},
 abstract = {© 2025 Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers Inc.. All rights reserved.Hypergraph partitioning plays a critical role in computer-aided design (CAD) because it allows us to break down a large circuit into several manageable pieces that facilitate efficient CAD algorithm designs. However, as circuit designs continue to grow in size, hypergraph partitioning becomes increasingly time-consuming. Recent research has introduced parallel hypergraph partitioners using multi-core CPUs to reduce the long runtime. However, the speedup of existing CPU parallel hypergraph partitioners is typically limited to a few cores. To overcome these challenges, we propose HyperG, a GPU-accelerated multilevel k-way hypergraph partitioning algorithm. HyperG introduces an innovative balanced group coarsening and a sequence-based refinement algorithm to accelerate both the coarsening and uncoarsening stages. Experimental results show that HyperG outperforms both the state-of-the-art sequential and CPU-based parallel partitioners with an average speedup of 133× and 4.1× while achieving comparable partitioning quality.},
