 abstract = {© 2025 Copyright is held by the owner/author(s). Publication rights licensed to ACM.The Number Theoretic Transform (NTT) significantly impacts the execution time of Fully Homomorphic Encryption (FHE) in practical applications, driving research into accelerated NTT methods. Computing-in-Memory (CIM) offers a promising solution to handle NTT's memory bottlenecks, yet efficiently implementing a CIM-based NTT engine remains challenging due to unique operations and large data sizes. We propose HP-CIM, a high-parallelism digital SRAM-based CIM NTT engine designed for large-scale NTT. HP-CIM integrates MVM-based NTT with a hierarchical SRAM architecture and novel even-odd data mapping, achieving nearly 3.08× faster execution and 4.96× energy savings compared to prior CIM-based designs.},
