@conference{Mitani20251432,
 abbrev_source_title = {Proc Asia South Pac Des Autom Conf},
 abstract = {© 2025 Copyright held by the owner/author(s).Applying electrical stress to MOS devices causes hydrogen bond breakage at the MOS interface. The released hydrogen diffuses away, leading to the creation of interface defects. The application of electrical stress creates bulk traps in the gate dielectrics simultaneously. However, the correlation between the released hydrogen and bulk trap creation has not been fully clarified yet.In this paper, to understand the relationship between the hydrogen release at the MOS interface and the interface / bulk trap creations, the MOSFET degradations under applying electrical stress have been investigated from the viewpoint of temperature dependence. As results, the obvious correlation between interface-trap generation and Ion degradation can be observed. However, Ion degradation is more pronounced at lower temperature in comparison to that at higher temperature. Furthermore, the transient electron trapping during VG - - ID measurement due to generated bulk defects is considered to the model for the degradation of MOSFET. It is inferred that the transient electron trapping accelerates the pronounced Ion degradation at cryogenic temperatures.},
